FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you
all so much for coming.

00:00:07.620 --> 00:00:10.330
It's my pleasure to introduce
our very special guest, Ira

00:00:10.330 --> 00:00:11.273
Glass.

00:00:11.273 --> 00:00:16.964
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:16.964 --> 00:00:18.630
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
as I'm sure you know,

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:21.570
Ira is the award winning
host and executive producer

00:00:21.570 --> 00:00:24.180
of the documentary radio
program, "This American

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:26.660
Life," produced by
Chicago Public Media

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:29.570
and distributed by Public
Radio International.

00:00:29.570 --> 00:00:31.730
The program began
in 1995 and is now

00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:34.320
heard on over 500
public radio stations

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:36.840
each week by more than
three million people

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:41.350
and is downloaded as a podcast
more than 900,000 times weekly.

00:00:41.350 --> 00:00:42.715
So Ira, thanks for joining us.

00:00:42.715 --> 00:00:43.840
IRA GLASS: Glad to be here.

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:44.490
FEMALE SPEAKER: I
want to start off

00:00:44.490 --> 00:00:46.198
with some basic
questions about the show.

00:00:46.198 --> 00:00:46.950
IRA GLASS: OK.

00:00:46.950 --> 00:00:49.158
FEMALE SPEAKER: Where you
get the ideas for the show?

00:00:49.158 --> 00:00:52.231
What comes first, the
theme or the stories?

00:00:52.231 --> 00:00:53.980
IRA GLASS: I mean, I
get asked this a lot.

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:56.000
I mean generally,
what will happen

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.270
is someone will pitch a story
which we just love as a staff.

00:01:01.270 --> 00:01:04.280
Every two weeks,
we have a meeting

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:05.940
where we generate
new story ideas,

00:01:05.940 --> 00:01:07.898
and then people are always
looking for stories.

00:01:07.898 --> 00:01:09.890
And so somebody
will pitch a story

00:01:09.890 --> 00:01:11.871
that we just all feel
very excited about

00:01:11.871 --> 00:01:13.620
and that doesn't go
with any of the themes

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:16.107
that we have going
on at the time,

00:01:16.107 --> 00:01:17.690
and so we'll just
basically say, look,

00:01:17.690 --> 00:01:20.410
let's do that story as the
anchor for some new show,

00:01:20.410 --> 00:01:24.786
and then we'll concoct a theme
that could possibly contain it.

00:01:24.786 --> 00:01:26.660
And sometimes we'll come
up with two or three

00:01:26.660 --> 00:01:28.780
different themes that
could possibly contain it,

00:01:28.780 --> 00:01:30.641
and then we'll look
on a list of here's

00:01:30.641 --> 00:01:32.640
some stories that are
left over from other shows

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:35.540
and we never used, and see if
we could glue anything to it,

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:37.594
and then we'll
start on a search.

00:01:37.594 --> 00:01:39.510
And then that search can
take us between three

00:01:39.510 --> 00:01:43.080
or four months often,
and sometimes even more,

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:48.130
and finding ideas for
stories is generally-- for us

00:01:48.130 --> 00:01:52.974
and I think for
anybody-- inefficient.

00:01:52.974 --> 00:01:54.390
I think one of the
things when you

00:01:54.390 --> 00:01:56.260
start to do creative
work that nobody really

00:01:56.260 --> 00:01:59.236
talks to you about is, where
are ideas going to come from?

00:01:59.236 --> 00:02:00.610
And you have this
idea of they're

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:03.320
going to be sprinkled on
your head like fairy dust.

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:05.870
And maybe this is it true in
engineering and other kinds

00:02:05.870 --> 00:02:08.910
of work, too, but
where I just come from

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:12.330
is you have to just surround
yourself with a lot of stuff

00:02:12.330 --> 00:02:15.530
and a lot of ideas because
ideas lead to other ideas.

00:02:15.530 --> 00:02:19.180
And so at some point, we'll just
go on a massive search which

00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:24.204
will include Googling,
but also just doing

00:02:24.204 --> 00:02:25.120
all kinds of research.

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:26.680
We'll brainstorm
different kinds of things

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:28.280
that could possibly
fit in the theme.

00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:29.654
Often, we're in
a situation where

00:02:29.654 --> 00:02:31.160
we'll have a very
serious story that

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:33.660
will be the anchor with a lot
of weight and a lot of stakes,

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:36.630
and so we'll just consciously
be looking for something

00:02:36.630 --> 00:02:44.120
funny or light or more personal
or small, just something

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:46.200
so the whole episode
won't be so heavy.

00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:49.960
And for us to find three
or four stories that'll

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:52.140
end up on the air,
often, we'll look

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:55.560
at 15 or 25 different
story ideas.

00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:58.120
And we'll go into production
often on seven or eight

00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:00.440
stories, and then we
just have to start

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:03.180
making them and
commissioning writers

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:04.680
and flying people
around the country

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:07.750
and interviewing
people, and then we

00:03:07.750 --> 00:03:10.150
kill a tremendous
amount of material.

00:03:10.150 --> 00:03:12.040
It just was built into
our production model

00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:13.831
from the beginning that
we would be killing

00:03:13.831 --> 00:03:16.785
between a third and a half
of everything we start.

00:03:16.785 --> 00:03:18.660
And it's sort of like
for the kind of stories

00:03:18.660 --> 00:03:22.930
we're doing where we need
them to be relatable,

00:03:22.930 --> 00:03:26.080
we need a strong
character-- at least one,

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:28.630
if not more than one-- we
need there to be a plot,

00:03:28.630 --> 00:03:30.190
the plot has to
be surprising, it

00:03:30.190 --> 00:03:32.870
has to do lead to some new
thought about the world,

00:03:32.870 --> 00:03:35.610
that thought has
to be surprising.

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:37.960
It's a lot of
criteria to have going

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:39.630
and you really can't
tell what's going

00:03:39.630 --> 00:03:41.380
to work until you start
to make the thing.

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:45.360
And so it's like
you want lightning

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:48.810
to strike as an industrial
product every week,

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:50.920
and to do that, you just
have to wander around

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:54.222
in the rain a lot.

00:03:54.222 --> 00:03:56.180
FEMALE SPEAKER: So learning
how much you record

00:03:56.180 --> 00:03:58.370
and how little of it
actually gets onto the show

00:03:58.370 --> 00:04:00.450
is pretty surprising to me.

00:04:00.450 --> 00:04:01.907
What else surprises people?

00:04:01.907 --> 00:04:04.240
IRA GLASS: Because in your
view, we just open up the mic

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:05.920
and people are
incredibly charming.

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:07.239
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yes.

00:04:07.239 --> 00:04:08.030
IRA GLASS: If only.

00:04:08.030 --> 00:04:08.990
FEMALE SPEAKER: I
think somebody comes up

00:04:08.990 --> 00:04:10.180
to you at a dinner
party and says,

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:11.870
Ira, I have this
great story, and then

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:13.460
you say, let's
record it right now,

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:15.510
and then suddenly it's
on the radio that week.

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:16.895
IRA GLASS: That
would be a dream.

00:04:16.895 --> 00:04:18.232
My job would be very easy.

00:04:18.232 --> 00:04:20.440
FEMALE SPEAKER: So what else
usually surprises people

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:24.040
about the production
of the show?

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:26.084
IRA GLASS: I mean,
it's a lot of us now.

00:04:26.084 --> 00:04:28.500
When we started the show, it
was just three people and me,

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:30.130
and now it's a dozen
of us making it.

00:04:30.130 --> 00:04:32.129
I don't know what would
be surprising to people.

00:04:35.884 --> 00:04:37.300
When you see a
movie, you can just

00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:38.580
feel all the money
and all the people

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:40.621
behind it, whereas a radio
show, if it's working,

00:04:40.621 --> 00:04:43.160
it just feels like one person
talking to another person,

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:45.800
and so the machinery
of it is invisible.

00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:47.700
If it's done well, you
don't get the feeling

00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:51.680
that we've spent four
months editing and reediting

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:55.210
and reediting and going
back and doing things again.

00:04:55.210 --> 00:04:57.585
So I think in general, the
machinery of it is surprising.

00:04:57.585 --> 00:04:59.334
FEMALE SPEAKER: What
about the interviews?

00:04:59.334 --> 00:05:00.790
Do you do them face to face?

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:03.350
IRA GLASS: Some, but it
doesn't have to face to face.

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:05.910
It's funny with radio,
I'll do interviews

00:05:05.910 --> 00:05:08.800
where I'll be in a
studio in one city

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:13.210
and somebody will be in
a studio in another city.

00:05:13.210 --> 00:05:17.380
And we use the incredibly
primitive technology of I'll

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:19.674
be in the studio and talking
to them over the phone,

00:05:19.674 --> 00:05:21.340
and we'll send an
engineer who will just

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:22.700
sit there with a microphone.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:24.375
So I'm recording
my voice where I am

00:05:24.375 --> 00:05:26.390
and they record their voice
on a recorder where they are,

00:05:26.390 --> 00:05:27.890
and then we just
synchronize the two

00:05:27.890 --> 00:05:30.470
tapes so it sounds like
we're in the same room.

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:32.150
Very complicated.

00:05:32.150 --> 00:05:36.486
And it turns out
for many things,

00:05:36.486 --> 00:05:38.360
that's just as good as
being there in person.

00:05:38.360 --> 00:05:39.734
It doesn't matter
if you're there

00:05:39.734 --> 00:05:41.960
for a lot of things, even
very personal things.

00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:43.418
Because it's almost
like we're used

00:05:43.418 --> 00:05:48.560
to talking to people on
the phone very personally,

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:51.040
and it's almost like the
conversation is happening

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:53.004
in the space of radio,
if that makes sense.

00:05:53.004 --> 00:05:54.420
And I know that
some interviewers,

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:56.290
like Terry Gross,
who does "Fresh Air,"

00:05:56.290 --> 00:05:59.272
she prefers not to be in
the studio with the people.

00:05:59.272 --> 00:06:00.480
She doesn't want to see them.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:03.030
She doesn't want them to see
her going through her notes.

00:06:04.939 --> 00:06:07.230
FEMALE SPEAKER: So I'd love
to hear you talk about some

00:06:07.230 --> 00:06:08.340
of your favorite episodes.

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:10.750
I know "Testosterone,"
I think is one of them,

00:06:10.750 --> 00:06:11.920
and "Hartford High."

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:14.782
What do you think makes
those so successful?

00:06:14.782 --> 00:06:16.990
IRA GLASS: I mean, those
are such different episodes.

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:22.340
I mean, the episodes
that are good

00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:25.310
have a really nice mix of
being relatable and surprising

00:06:25.310 --> 00:06:30.630
and take you into a world
that you kind of know

00:06:30.630 --> 00:06:34.690
exists but don't really
know the details of.

00:06:34.690 --> 00:06:38.720
"Harper High School," it
was a two episode thing.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:39.890
We'd never done that before.

00:06:39.890 --> 00:06:42.150
And basically, it came out
of our senior producer,

00:06:42.150 --> 00:06:45.070
Julie Snyder, being really
interested in trying

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:50.840
to figure out a way to cover
gun violence in Chicago.

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:54.430
Last year, 506 people,
I think it was,

00:06:54.430 --> 00:06:57.277
were shot in one
year in Chicago,

00:06:57.277 --> 00:06:59.360
and the number was going
up whereas the number was

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:02.300
going down or staying the
same in other big cities,

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:06.560
and it was very unclear why the
number was so high in Chicago.

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:08.790
560 is a huge number.

00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:12.000
New York is three times
larger than Chicago,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.290
and the number of shootings in
New York was smaller than that.

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:19.410
And in the coverage
of it, it was

00:07:19.410 --> 00:07:22.250
really hard to even understand
the most basic things

00:07:22.250 --> 00:07:24.330
like, why are people
shooting each other?

00:07:24.330 --> 00:07:26.810
You would read in the
clippings, so somebody got shot

00:07:26.810 --> 00:07:30.010
at the corner of 70th and Stony
Island, and you wouldn't know.

00:07:30.010 --> 00:07:31.560
Was it a drug thing?

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:32.431
Was it a gang thing?

00:07:32.431 --> 00:07:33.430
Was it a domestic thing?

00:07:33.430 --> 00:07:34.840
You couldn't even know.

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:39.400
And so we were looking for
a way to get a grip on it,

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:43.790
and if you're us, the
first thing we need

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:45.780
is plot and story
and characters,

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:48.490
and so we have to find a
place to locate the story.

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:53.460
And the first thing we tried was
on Memorial Day of that year,

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:55.234
50 people were shot
in one weekend,

00:07:55.234 --> 00:07:56.400
in the Memorial Day weekend.

00:07:56.400 --> 00:07:58.270
We felt like, OK,
that'll be our frame.

00:07:58.270 --> 00:08:00.560
We'll just do
Memorial Day weekend

00:08:00.560 --> 00:08:04.760
and we'll do those 50 shootings.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:09.270
And that turned out to be
unproducable in the time frame

00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:11.485
we wanted because once
the people were caught up

00:08:11.485 --> 00:08:13.970
in the court system, we couldn't
get people to talk to us,

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:16.355
and we couldn't report out the
stories with the kind of speed

00:08:16.355 --> 00:08:17.870
that you'd want to
to get it on the air.

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:19.160
And then we went looking
for another frame

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:21.650
and we found this high
school, Harper High School,

00:08:21.650 --> 00:08:25.940
where 29 kids had
been shot in one year.

00:08:25.940 --> 00:08:27.830
I can't remember
if it's nine-- they

00:08:27.830 --> 00:08:29.770
were current or recent students.

00:08:29.770 --> 00:08:32.268
So recent students are sort
of like a kid who dropped out

00:08:32.268 --> 00:08:34.809
as a sophomore, but now he would
have been in his junior year

00:08:34.809 --> 00:08:36.767
and still friends with
everybody in the school.

00:08:36.767 --> 00:08:39.900
We were counting those because
the school counted them.

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:42.309
So it was 29 current
and recent students

00:08:42.309 --> 00:08:45.722
and eight or nine of
them died in one year.

00:08:45.722 --> 00:08:47.305
And if you just think
about the trauma

00:08:47.305 --> 00:08:49.480
a school goes through
if there's one shooting,

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:51.130
and so this is 29 of them.

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:54.120
And this wasn't
the most shootings

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:55.781
in Chicago or anything.

00:08:55.781 --> 00:08:57.780
And I think what makes
an episode like that work

00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:00.260
is that, honestly, most of
us have no idea what it's

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:03.010
like to live in a community
where that many people are

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:05.390
getting shot.

00:09:05.390 --> 00:09:07.960
We sent in three
reporters for five months

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:09.600
to just camp out in
that school and get

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:13.010
to know the staff
and the students.

00:09:13.010 --> 00:09:17.920
And what was interesting
was both being

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:21.130
able to document what
that level of violence

00:09:21.130 --> 00:09:23.990
does to the kids with
the kind of detail

00:09:23.990 --> 00:09:26.200
that you don't get to
report out that much.

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:31.130
And so there was one kid
who was like the Forrest

00:09:31.130 --> 00:09:32.630
Gump of the shootings
at the school.

00:09:32.630 --> 00:09:36.670
He had been at six or
seven different shootings,

00:09:36.670 --> 00:09:39.090
kids who he knows, close to.

00:09:39.090 --> 00:09:41.380
He would just be standing
there, they would die right

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:42.921
in front of them,
and his own brother

00:09:42.921 --> 00:09:46.060
had been shot three
times and survived,

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:49.960
but was in a wheelchair at
the end of the last shooting.

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:55.730
And where that kid is
after that turns out

00:09:55.730 --> 00:09:59.677
to be something
worth talking about.

00:09:59.677 --> 00:10:01.760
And then the staff of the
school was really great,

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:06.740
kind of the crypto message
of the show, I guess,

00:10:06.740 --> 00:10:08.580
was here is like an
inner city high school,

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:10.204
and people bring all
these associations

00:10:10.204 --> 00:10:13.170
to that, and the
super competent staff.

00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:15.670
And when there was a shooting,
they had all these procedures

00:10:15.670 --> 00:10:18.030
that they had developed,
learning from the Army

00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:20.360
these after action reports
where they would just

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:22.850
jump into action to figure
out, if this kid got shot,

00:10:22.850 --> 00:10:24.272
who else did this kid know?

00:10:24.272 --> 00:10:25.230
What gang were they in?

00:10:25.230 --> 00:10:26.420
What gang is warring
with that gang?

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:28.961
And they would just get all the
other kids who could possibly

00:10:28.961 --> 00:10:31.930
get shot out of the
school and to their homes

00:10:31.930 --> 00:10:34.020
to get people to safety.

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:42.940
And just so much about that
show was really surprising,

00:10:42.940 --> 00:10:45.820
so that made that work.

00:10:45.820 --> 00:10:48.389
I could talk about this
show for a long time.

00:10:48.389 --> 00:10:50.680
Gangs in that school turned
out to be really different.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:52.730
It made me feel like
such an old person.

00:10:52.730 --> 00:10:55.440
The gangs, when I was a
reporter in Chicago reporting

00:10:55.440 --> 00:11:00.654
on gangs 15, 20 years ago,
gangs were a criminal enterprise

00:11:00.654 --> 00:11:02.820
like you'd see on "The
Wire," and they'd sell drugs,

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:03.710
and they were out to make money.

00:11:03.710 --> 00:11:05.335
And I just felt like,
these kids today,

00:11:05.335 --> 00:11:06.960
they don't even
want to make money.

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:10.390
They're not even selling drugs.

00:11:10.390 --> 00:11:12.610
And the parents are
sort of like what I was.

00:11:12.610 --> 00:11:14.800
They thought a street
gang was one thing,

00:11:14.800 --> 00:11:18.540
and all these things are--
if you heard the show,

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:20.380
it's like your
high school clique.

00:11:20.380 --> 00:11:22.540
And it's just like
a bunch of kids,

00:11:22.540 --> 00:11:25.180
but everybody can get a gun.

00:11:25.180 --> 00:11:28.050
And so it's just like
basically, the neighborhood

00:11:28.050 --> 00:11:31.060
is so dangerous, every kid
in the school was in a gang.

00:11:33.810 --> 00:11:37.080
The nerds were in the gangs, the
drama kids were in the gangs,

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:38.860
the band kids were in the gang.

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:40.450
Every kid, you had
to be in a gang.

00:11:40.450 --> 00:11:42.070
Every kid was in a gang.

00:11:42.070 --> 00:11:45.750
And so you'd read
about this 15-year-old

00:11:45.750 --> 00:11:47.890
that summer got shot.

00:11:47.890 --> 00:11:50.400
And you'd read in the paper,
she was a member of a gang.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:52.150
Every kid is in the gang.

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:53.710
She was a band kid.

00:12:00.390 --> 00:12:01.980
So a lot of that was
surprising, and I

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:03.480
feel like that's
what makes it good.

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:05.090
There were characters
who, when you

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:12.990
would hear their situation--
the secret power of the radio

00:12:12.990 --> 00:12:16.080
or the special power of
doing something on the radio

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:19.480
is the fact that
you don't see them.

00:12:19.480 --> 00:12:21.600
It's easy to create
the kind of intimacy

00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:25.020
where you feel like you can
get to know people very,

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:27.330
very quickly.

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:31.170
We did a TV show for two years
and we've done two movies,

00:12:31.170 --> 00:12:35.630
and I feel like you can
create that kind of intimacy

00:12:35.630 --> 00:12:39.490
on film or on video,
but you'd really

00:12:39.490 --> 00:12:41.530
have to shoot it like a film.

00:12:41.530 --> 00:12:42.950
You'd have to light
it beautifully

00:12:42.950 --> 00:12:45.610
you'd have to like really
frame it beautifully,

00:12:45.610 --> 00:12:47.670
and just to bring the
kind of production values

00:12:47.670 --> 00:12:50.110
that you'd have to bring
to it to make those stories

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:53.980
work with the sort of immediacy
and emotional intimacy

00:12:53.980 --> 00:12:55.440
that you get on
radio, you'd have

00:12:55.440 --> 00:13:01.480
to really throw a tremendous
amount of money and production

00:13:01.480 --> 00:13:02.140
value at it.

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:04.700
It really would have
to be shot like a film,

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:06.982
whereas with us, we're going
out with tape recorders.

00:13:06.982 --> 00:13:08.940
And just the fact that
you don't see the people

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:12.747
and you hear their voice, that
has such an immediacy to it

00:13:12.747 --> 00:13:15.080
that I feel like that's the
special power that radio can

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:16.770
bring to something like that.

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:20.750
And you just feel like you
get to know the people so fast

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:22.630
and you're so close
up in their world

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:24.580
that it's easy to
imagine, here's

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:26.900
what it would be
like to be them.

00:13:26.900 --> 00:13:30.310
I mean, this is a really
long answer to your question,

00:13:30.310 --> 00:13:33.000
but I feel like
the thing that we

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.320
can contribute as reporters
in the world that is harder

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:41.800
to achieve than other
kinds of journalism

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:44.310
is to do the most basic
thing that a story can do,

00:13:44.310 --> 00:13:47.670
which is make it possible
to imagine, oh, here's

00:13:47.670 --> 00:13:49.439
what it would be like to be you.

00:13:49.439 --> 00:13:51.480
And I feel like something
like that, where you're

00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:53.670
talking about gang kids
and things like that, where

00:13:53.670 --> 00:13:55.171
I think people who
are not in a gang

00:13:55.171 --> 00:13:57.086
or didn't grow up in
that kind of neighborhood

00:13:57.086 --> 00:13:58.762
bring all kinds of
associations to it,

00:13:58.762 --> 00:14:00.195
to be able to illustrate,
no, no, no, here's

00:14:00.195 --> 00:14:00.830
what it's really like.

00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:01.910
If you lived in
this neighborhood,

00:14:01.910 --> 00:14:03.170
you would be in the gang.

00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:08.080
Here's how you would feel
and here's how you would be.

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:11.606
That's what we're trying.

00:14:11.606 --> 00:14:12.950
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:14:12.950 --> 00:14:14.449
IRA GLASS: Oh my
god that was silly.

00:14:14.449 --> 00:14:16.120
Too long.

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:19.115
I'll be more terse as we go on.

00:14:19.115 --> 00:14:20.990
FEMALE SPEAKER: So when
I heard that episode,

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:23.031
it was very affecting,
and you leave that episode

00:14:23.031 --> 00:14:24.537
and you say, what
can I do to help?

00:14:24.537 --> 00:14:26.870
And I think there was some
sort of donations for Harper.

00:14:26.870 --> 00:14:28.357
Was there on the website?

00:14:28.357 --> 00:14:30.190
IRA GLASS: The school
set up a donation page

00:14:30.190 --> 00:14:31.856
and they made a quarter
million dollars.

00:14:31.856 --> 00:14:34.440
And if anybody wants to
go, they can use the money.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:35.880
They're a public school.

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:37.770
But what can you do to help?

00:14:37.770 --> 00:14:40.710
There's nothing
you can do to help.

00:14:40.710 --> 00:14:41.790
Nothing you can do.

00:14:41.790 --> 00:14:48.360
I honestly believe it wasn't the
kind of thing where-- I mean,

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:51.310
maybe it's cynical to
say that, but are you

00:14:51.310 --> 00:14:54.630
going to change the social
structure of the south side

00:14:54.630 --> 00:14:57.670
of Chicago so that kids don't
want to join gangs, or make

00:14:57.670 --> 00:14:59.681
the neighborhood a
safe neighborhood?

00:14:59.681 --> 00:15:01.180
I mean, you know
how you could help,

00:15:01.180 --> 00:15:05.040
is if you could revive
the economy of that part

00:15:05.040 --> 00:15:09.680
of the city of Chicago so that
the entire neighborhood became

00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:11.747
safer because the
economic level would rise.

00:15:11.747 --> 00:15:13.080
I think that would be the thing.

00:15:13.080 --> 00:15:15.700
But the fact is in our country,
where pockets of violence

00:15:15.700 --> 00:15:20.740
happen, it's very poor
pockets in cities,

00:15:20.740 --> 00:15:24.874
and unless you fix that.

00:15:24.874 --> 00:15:26.290
FEMALE SPEAKER:
But with episodes,

00:15:26.290 --> 00:15:30.060
like "Very Tough Love," you
made the story, I think,

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:32.080
because you wanted to
tell that story, but--

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:33.840
IRA GLASS: "Very Tough
Love," it's about this judge.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:35.464
There was a judge
down in Georgia who--

00:15:35.464 --> 00:15:38.450
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yeah, Judge
Amanda Williams was in Georgia,

00:15:38.450 --> 00:15:41.560
and there was an episode about
her drug corps and some very

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:42.360
strict rulings.

00:15:42.360 --> 00:15:43.872
And then after
the episode aired,

00:15:43.872 --> 00:15:46.244
there were some real world
consequences for her.

00:15:46.244 --> 00:15:48.660
So when you told that story,
were you thinking in the back

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:50.076
to your mind,
what's Georgia going

00:15:50.076 --> 00:15:51.510
to do once this
airs, or were you

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:55.590
just telling it to tell
an interesting story?

00:15:55.590 --> 00:15:57.510
IRA GLASS: I mean, it
was first and foremost

00:15:57.510 --> 00:16:00.626
an interesting story.

00:16:00.626 --> 00:16:03.214
That story, man.

00:16:03.214 --> 00:16:04.130
I was down in Georgia.

00:16:04.130 --> 00:16:07.060
We had this idea for a show
called "Georgia Rambler," based

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:08.905
on an old newspaper
column, and the idea

00:16:08.905 --> 00:16:11.630
is that this guy would roll
into different small towns

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:15.557
in Georgia, this
columnist, Charles Salter.

00:16:15.557 --> 00:16:17.140
He would just show
up in a town and he

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:20.220
would find a story that
day about that town,

00:16:20.220 --> 00:16:22.120
and it was just portraits
of small town life.

00:16:22.120 --> 00:16:24.257
And as a staff, we just
thought, that would be fun.

00:16:24.257 --> 00:16:24.840
Let's do that.

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:25.923
So we each chose a county.

00:16:25.923 --> 00:16:28.100
We'd just pick
names out of a hat.

00:16:28.100 --> 00:16:32.390
And so I ended up with
the county that turned out

00:16:32.390 --> 00:16:34.620
to be the county that
this judge was in,

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:37.800
and you're given one day to
find a story under these rules

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:39.760
that we artificially
created for ourselves just

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:41.120
to amuse ourselves.

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:46.450
And I had been in the county--
literally the first interview

00:16:46.450 --> 00:16:49.380
I did was somebody who was like,
you know who you should talk

00:16:49.380 --> 00:16:51.460
to is this guy, Joe
[INAUDIBLE], and he's

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:53.000
in this war with this judge.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.480
And I heard about
the judge right away,

00:16:56.480 --> 00:16:59.610
and people kept telling me
stories about the judge.

00:16:59.610 --> 00:17:04.819
And I totally had this feeling
of, if these stories are true,

00:17:04.819 --> 00:17:07.859
somebody should really
investigate this judge.

00:17:07.859 --> 00:17:09.800
And I totally had
the feeling of,

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:11.329
some reporter should
come down here.

00:17:15.172 --> 00:17:17.380
And honestly, when people
would tell me these stores,

00:17:17.380 --> 00:17:20.770
I couldn't tell if
the stories were true.

00:17:20.770 --> 00:17:23.069
I really had a feeling
of, this can't be true.

00:17:23.069 --> 00:17:24.980
And then pinning it
down and getting people

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:28.369
to go on the record took
four or five months.

00:17:28.369 --> 00:17:30.940
Every time I would fly back
down there, my wife and my staff

00:17:30.940 --> 00:17:33.910
were just like, why are
you doing this story?

00:17:33.910 --> 00:17:36.780
And then it turned
out people were

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:38.860
willing to come forward
and go on the record.

00:17:38.860 --> 00:17:41.110
And I did have a feeling
in the back of my mind,

00:17:41.110 --> 00:17:44.550
somebody should do something
about this if this is true.

00:17:44.550 --> 00:17:47.501
And I don't feel like
I can claim credit.

00:17:47.501 --> 00:17:49.750
At the same time that people
were saying things to me,

00:17:49.750 --> 00:17:53.770
they were saying things to--
there's a watchdog state

00:17:53.770 --> 00:17:56.550
committee that looks for judges
who might be doing things that

00:17:56.550 --> 00:17:59.800
are bad, and they had been
tipped off about this judge

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:01.770
and they were
looking into it too.

00:18:01.770 --> 00:18:05.079
But I think the visibility of
the radio show and the fact

00:18:05.079 --> 00:18:06.620
that people from
all over the country

00:18:06.620 --> 00:18:11.290
heard it gave it a
visibility in Georgia.

00:18:11.290 --> 00:18:14.910
And honestly, hearing it
on the radio, a woman who

00:18:14.910 --> 00:18:17.360
had been on the
State Supreme Court

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:19.660
got involved in the case
as one of the people moving

00:18:19.660 --> 00:18:21.880
the case forward.

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:25.670
It raised the profile of it
in a way that is very rare.

00:18:25.670 --> 00:18:30.660
Honestly, most journalism
doesn't achieve anything.

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:33.850
And I think I got
into journalism,

00:18:33.850 --> 00:18:37.470
like most young
people, thinking,

00:18:37.470 --> 00:18:39.000
I'm going to make
the world a better

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.790
place by exposing wrongdoing.

00:18:41.790 --> 00:18:44.440
But honestly, most
wrongdoing that you expose,

00:18:44.440 --> 00:18:47.250
nothing happens.

00:18:47.250 --> 00:18:51.630
You can do all the stories you
want on Guantanamo and things

00:18:51.630 --> 00:18:57.710
that somebody should get in
there and fix-- climate change.

00:18:57.710 --> 00:19:00.810
Everybody who is going to
believe that climate change is

00:19:00.810 --> 00:19:03.390
real pretty much believes it,
and yet we're not actually

00:19:03.390 --> 00:19:06.060
addressing the
problem in a way that

00:19:06.060 --> 00:19:08.840
is at the scale of
the problem itself.

00:19:08.840 --> 00:19:12.200
And I just feel like, what
is left to say as a reporter?

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:15.230
It's happening, there's more
and more evidence all the time.

00:19:15.230 --> 00:19:19.400
We can say it again,
but you already know it.

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:21.120
And so generally, when
you're a reporter,

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:23.491
almost nothing gets
any results ever.

00:19:23.491 --> 00:19:25.240
That's one of the very
few times I've ever

00:19:25.240 --> 00:19:27.790
worked on anything that
I could say afterwards,

00:19:27.790 --> 00:19:30.572
I helped in any way the
process of something changing.

00:19:30.572 --> 00:19:32.780
FEMALE SPEAKER: What about
people's individual lives?

00:19:32.780 --> 00:19:35.280
Do they follow up with you and
say, after I was on the show,

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:36.859
this happened?

00:19:36.859 --> 00:19:39.150
IRA GLASS: After I was on
the show, a lot of my friends

00:19:39.150 --> 00:19:42.380
got in contact with
me over Twitter.

00:19:42.380 --> 00:19:43.820
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Real world change.

00:19:43.820 --> 00:19:46.531
IRA GLASS: Real world change.

00:19:46.531 --> 00:19:47.280
I mean, sometimes.

00:19:51.650 --> 00:19:57.030
Often, we're just documenting
people's personal stories,

00:19:57.030 --> 00:20:03.392
and I don't know how much--
I mean, I don't know.

00:20:03.392 --> 00:20:05.850
FEMALE SPEAKER: Maybe they
would get back in touch with you

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:08.480
and say, hey Ira, I was really
having a problem with that.

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:09.530
Now it worked out.

00:20:09.530 --> 00:20:11.350
Or just wanted to let you know.

00:20:14.090 --> 00:20:15.974
IRA GLASS: No, not that often.

00:20:15.974 --> 00:20:18.670
No, no, no.

00:20:18.670 --> 00:20:21.201
Like, no, I told that story
about my mom and she heard it

00:20:21.201 --> 00:20:22.200
and now she's mad at me.

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:25.222
There's a little bit of that.

00:20:25.222 --> 00:20:27.430
FEMALE SPEAKER: What about
episodes that just flopped

00:20:27.430 --> 00:20:29.850
or made you uncomfortable
or maybe listening back

00:20:29.850 --> 00:20:32.080
to some old ones, you feel
like you didn't cover them

00:20:32.080 --> 00:20:34.190
in the way you would now?

00:20:34.190 --> 00:20:38.890
IRA GLASS: I mean, there
definitely are things-- yeah,

00:20:38.890 --> 00:20:39.850
there's a lot.

00:20:39.850 --> 00:20:41.220
I mean, we're on a lot.

00:20:41.220 --> 00:20:43.020
We made a lot of episodes.

00:20:43.020 --> 00:20:45.220
And there are
things, definitely,

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:50.115
that I really wish we
could have done better.

00:20:53.170 --> 00:20:54.620
I wish I could
think of an example

00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:57.010
very quickly for you of one.

00:21:00.160 --> 00:21:05.020
There's one that we did
last week that on staff, we

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:07.900
wondered if we handled literally
the structure of the show

00:21:07.900 --> 00:21:09.170
properly.

00:21:09.170 --> 00:21:11.960
And it was this one which
was built around an idea

00:21:11.960 --> 00:21:12.650
that I love.

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:15.280
One of our producers,
Sarah Koenig, her mom

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:17.620
has seven rules on things
you should never talk about.

00:21:20.697 --> 00:21:22.530
Unless you're going
through a health crisis,

00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:24.200
you should never talk
about your health,

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:26.034
like oh, I have this
problem in my shoulder.

00:21:26.034 --> 00:21:27.700
You should never talk
about your dreams.

00:21:27.700 --> 00:21:29.910
You should never talk about
how you slept last night,

00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:33.360
and number one on her list the
route you took to get there.

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:34.810
Nobody's interested.

00:21:34.810 --> 00:21:36.830
And so she has seven
stories, and we thought,

00:21:36.830 --> 00:21:38.538
this a really funny
premise for the show.

00:21:38.538 --> 00:21:41.140
And Sarah said, well, what
if we could prove you wrong?

00:21:41.140 --> 00:21:42.920
I work with a team of people.

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:45.470
We're very committed to
finding interesting stories

00:21:45.470 --> 00:21:46.430
on any subject.

00:21:46.430 --> 00:21:50.102
What if we can prove that there
could be stories on these seven

00:21:50.102 --> 00:21:51.560
subjects that could
be interesting?

00:21:51.560 --> 00:21:53.810
And her mother is like, I
don't believe you can do it.

00:21:53.810 --> 00:21:56.800
And then it was
very much like, OK,

00:21:56.800 --> 00:21:59.359
the first scene
of "My Fair Lady."

00:21:59.359 --> 00:22:01.150
I can take this woman
with a cockney accent

00:22:01.150 --> 00:22:02.191
and make her into a lady.

00:22:04.840 --> 00:22:05.880
That's our mission.

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:08.790
And so we set out as a staff
to find seven stories that

00:22:08.790 --> 00:22:13.420
would totally be amazing
stories of those seven subjects.

00:22:13.420 --> 00:22:17.555
And Sarah Koenig is just such an
amazing interviewer and writer

00:22:17.555 --> 00:22:18.430
on the radio.

00:22:24.290 --> 00:22:26.580
And somehow, when
the show was done,

00:22:26.580 --> 00:22:28.420
all of a sudden the
feeling of, oh wait,

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:29.690
did we format the show wrong?

00:22:29.690 --> 00:22:31.360
And this is such a
nerdy thing, but we

00:22:31.360 --> 00:22:33.830
keep coming back to the
mom throughout the hour

00:22:33.830 --> 00:22:35.570
to check in of like, well,
what did you think of that one?

00:22:35.570 --> 00:22:36.970
What did you think of that one?

00:22:36.970 --> 00:22:38.600
And then we realized
at the end-- which

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:40.510
seemed like since
there's a drama of what

00:22:40.510 --> 00:22:41.760
is she going to
think of each story

00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:44.009
and is she going to give the
thumbs up or thumbs down?

00:22:44.009 --> 00:22:46.810
But somehow, weirdly,
I think for listeners,

00:22:46.810 --> 00:22:48.080
that lowered the stakes.

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:49.780
Did you guys hear this one?

00:22:49.780 --> 00:22:52.225
Was it a thumbs up or
thumbs down episode?

00:22:52.225 --> 00:22:53.134
Thumbs up?

00:22:53.134 --> 00:22:55.050
How many of you are
thumbs down on it, though?

00:22:55.050 --> 00:22:56.170
Some thumbs down.

00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:59.810
Because the drama
doesn't play perfectly.

00:22:59.810 --> 00:23:03.200
And some of the staffers-- I
was very much on the side of,

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:05.362
we must have the
mom in the studio

00:23:05.362 --> 00:23:07.820
because the drama is, is the
mom going to give us thumbs up

00:23:07.820 --> 00:23:08.445
or thumbs down?

00:23:08.445 --> 00:23:12.320
And we'll just do it like we'll
tell the stories to the mom.

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:14.635
And then there was a
whole contingent on staff

00:23:14.635 --> 00:23:15.927
