00:57:04.023 --> 00:57:07.070
there's a universal quality to
them that could be anywhere.

00:57:07.070 --> 00:57:09.090
But also, we happen
to be Americans.

00:57:09.090 --> 00:57:10.560
Our tastes are
American, the things

00:57:10.560 --> 00:57:11.810
that interest us are American.

00:57:11.810 --> 00:57:14.850
So I feel like it's kind of
both things at the same time.

00:57:14.850 --> 00:57:18.040
AUDIENCE: You recently
rebroadcasted an updated

00:57:18.040 --> 00:57:20.400
version of an older episode
that I really loved,

00:57:20.400 --> 00:57:21.435
the "Fiasco" episode.

00:57:21.435 --> 00:57:22.060
IRA GLASS: Yes.

00:57:22.060 --> 00:57:22.960
AUDIENCE: And one
of the segments

00:57:22.960 --> 00:57:25.070
in the "Fiasco" episode
is a reporter talking

00:57:25.070 --> 00:57:28.610
about her fiasco interview,
and I was really curious

00:57:28.610 --> 00:57:31.260
if you ever had an
interview or an experience

00:57:31.260 --> 00:57:34.330
producing the show that you
would describe as a fiasco,

00:57:34.330 --> 00:57:35.855
and if so, what was it?

00:57:35.855 --> 00:57:37.230
IRA GLASS: I
haven't had anything

00:57:37.230 --> 00:57:39.850
as spectacular as that reporter
who, in the middle of a very

00:57:39.850 --> 00:57:42.520
tense interview, squirted
coffee or iced tea

00:57:42.520 --> 00:57:46.530
or something out of her
nose, bringing her interview

00:57:46.530 --> 00:57:52.110
to a stop and simultaneously
winning over the interviewee.

00:57:52.110 --> 00:57:55.040
So I don't have as dramatic
a story as that to tell.

00:57:55.040 --> 00:57:57.740
A lot of things have gone really
badly for me in interviews.

00:57:57.740 --> 00:58:00.200
When you do a lot of interviews,
you make every mistake.

00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:02.320
But I don't have
an answer that's

00:58:02.320 --> 00:58:03.570
to the level of your question.

00:58:03.570 --> 00:58:05.319
AUDIENCE: Anything
particularly noteworthy

00:58:05.319 --> 00:58:07.520
that's not at the level
of that kind of a fiasco?

00:58:11.155 --> 00:58:12.030
It's OK if you don't.

00:58:12.030 --> 00:58:12.780
IRA GLASS: Nothing
comes to mind.

00:58:12.780 --> 00:58:14.750
It's a really good question,
but I don't have an answer.

00:58:14.750 --> 00:58:15.291
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:58:15.291 --> 00:58:15.956
Well, thanks.

00:58:15.956 --> 00:58:18.330
IRA GLASS: Which is honestly
a real interviewing problem.

00:58:18.330 --> 00:58:20.040
Often, the question is
better than any answer

00:58:20.040 --> 00:58:21.498
that the interviewee
comes up with.

00:58:21.498 --> 00:58:24.180
So my heart goes out to
you in your excellence

00:58:24.180 --> 00:58:27.491
and in my failure to rise to
the excellence of your question.

00:58:27.491 --> 00:58:27.990
Yes?

00:58:27.990 --> 00:58:29.025
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:58:29.025 --> 00:58:29.900
I have two questions.

00:58:29.900 --> 00:58:34.340
Do you have any dream episodes
or goals for the next 10 years

00:58:34.340 --> 00:58:35.140
for the show?

00:58:35.140 --> 00:58:38.450
And then also, I was listening
to the "Superhero" episode--

00:58:38.450 --> 00:58:40.930
IRA GLASS: Let me
answer that one first.

00:58:40.930 --> 00:58:43.390
I'm constantly having dream
episodes and ideas for things

00:58:43.390 --> 00:58:45.860
we want to do, but
then we do them.

00:58:45.860 --> 00:58:50.430
It's kind of a rolling project.

00:58:50.430 --> 00:58:55.670
Let me think if there's anything
in particular right this day.

00:58:55.670 --> 00:58:57.440
No, nothing today.

00:58:57.440 --> 00:58:59.441
I feel like the stuff
that we want to do, we do,

00:58:59.441 --> 00:59:00.940
but I don't have
anything right now.

00:59:00.940 --> 00:59:01.570
What else?

00:59:01.570 --> 00:59:04.028
AUDIENCE: And then after the
"Superhero" episode, would you

00:59:04.028 --> 00:59:05.620
choose flight or
invisibility and why?

00:59:05.620 --> 00:59:07.703
IRA GLASS: I absolutely
would choose invisibility.

00:59:07.703 --> 00:59:10.630
I know myself very
well, and the kind

00:59:10.630 --> 00:59:14.430
of crouching, lurking,
nobody can see me,

00:59:14.430 --> 00:59:16.420
I will watch you
sort of situation,

00:59:16.420 --> 00:59:18.730
I'm totally comfortable with.

00:59:18.730 --> 00:59:19.370
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:59:19.370 --> 00:59:21.475
IRA GLASS: Flying
from place to place,

00:59:21.475 --> 00:59:24.420
I can buy a ticket
on an airplane.

00:59:24.420 --> 00:59:26.290
AUDIENCE: Airplanes
are so terrible.

00:59:26.290 --> 00:59:27.040
IRA GLASS: Really?

00:59:27.040 --> 00:59:27.540
No.

00:59:27.540 --> 00:59:28.930
I don't feel that way at all.

00:59:28.930 --> 00:59:30.250
AUDIENCE: Have you ever
had a really good story

00:59:30.250 --> 00:59:30.875
on an airplane?

00:59:33.260 --> 00:59:35.150
IRA GLASS: No, because
any really good story

00:59:35.150 --> 00:59:37.072
would involve near
death whatever.

00:59:37.072 --> 00:59:38.530
I'm happy to keep
it the way it is.

00:59:38.530 --> 00:59:40.430
No, airplanes are amazing.

00:59:40.430 --> 00:59:42.555
I can't believe you're
complaining about airplanes.

00:59:42.555 --> 00:59:45.130
That's a technology which
is totally wonderful.

00:59:45.130 --> 00:59:48.617
You get on an object that
moves you really fast,

00:59:48.617 --> 00:59:50.200
and it's super
comfortable, and nobody

00:59:50.200 --> 00:59:53.020
can reach you on
the phone so far.

00:59:53.020 --> 00:59:53.810
It's awesome.

00:59:53.810 --> 00:59:56.079
Every part of it is great.

00:59:56.079 --> 00:59:57.620
AUDIENCE: You must
be in first class.

00:59:57.620 --> 00:59:58.230
IRA GLASS: What?

00:59:58.230 --> 00:59:59.770
AUDIENCE: You must
be in first class.

00:59:59.770 --> 01:00:00.060
IRA GLASS: No.

01:00:00.060 --> 01:00:01.300
I am so not in first class.

01:00:04.375 --> 01:00:05.671
Are you kidding?

01:00:05.671 --> 01:00:06.170
No.

01:00:06.170 --> 01:00:08.990
I spilled coffee in the car
on the way over here and I

01:00:08.990 --> 01:00:11.960
didn't-- that's the
level that I'm at.

01:00:11.960 --> 01:00:15.039
No, no, no, no.

01:00:15.039 --> 01:00:16.080
I can tell you one thing.

01:00:16.080 --> 01:00:18.960
We are talking about
starting another podcast.

01:00:18.960 --> 01:00:22.117
That's one dream for the
show, is that a bunch of us

01:00:22.117 --> 01:00:23.950
feel like we should
start making more stuff,

01:00:23.950 --> 01:00:25.210
and hopefully in
the next year, we'll

01:00:25.210 --> 01:00:26.584
be coming out with
more podcasts.

01:00:26.584 --> 01:00:29.280
And one idea that we're
really excited about

01:00:29.280 --> 01:00:31.510
is the idea that we would
do a show that's exactly

01:00:31.510 --> 01:00:34.210
the opposite of our show
and do it as a podcast,

01:00:34.210 --> 01:00:36.297
and instead of it being
each week we choose

01:00:36.297 --> 01:00:38.880
a different theme, we would do
the thing that journalism never

01:00:38.880 --> 01:00:40.470
does, and every week,
we would go back

01:00:40.470 --> 01:00:43.840
to exactly the same story and
give you the next chapter of it

01:00:43.840 --> 01:00:45.250
and let it unfold over time.

01:00:45.250 --> 01:00:46.750
And so we're hoping
to roll that out

01:00:46.750 --> 01:00:50.156
in January if all
goes as planned.

01:00:50.156 --> 01:00:52.530
We just started talking about
it in the last week or two,

01:00:52.530 --> 01:00:53.946
so maybe it's not
going to happen,

01:00:53.946 --> 01:00:56.370
but I feel like it would
be really exciting,

01:00:56.370 --> 01:01:00.251
and hopefully the first
of other projects.

01:01:00.251 --> 01:01:02.250
AUDIENCE: That leads
perfectly into my question.

01:01:02.250 --> 01:01:03.920
The first "This
American Life" episode

01:01:03.920 --> 01:01:06.640
I remember listening to on
the radio in high school

01:01:06.640 --> 01:01:08.370
was about undocumented
immigrants

01:01:08.370 --> 01:01:11.530
who got caught up in jail
for some minor offense

01:01:11.530 --> 01:01:14.220
and then were never able to
get out because they didn't

01:01:14.220 --> 01:01:16.490
have proper documentation.

01:01:16.490 --> 01:01:18.740
I always wonder when I
listen to these stories, what

01:01:18.740 --> 01:01:20.820
happens to these people
five, ten years down

01:01:20.820 --> 01:01:24.510
the road, or even a couple
months, in some cases.

01:01:24.510 --> 01:01:26.600
You just mentioned you
might start a podcast where

01:01:26.600 --> 01:01:29.740
you follow up with the people
in your previous stories.

01:01:29.740 --> 01:01:32.750
I'm sure that
manpower is a factor.

01:01:32.750 --> 01:01:35.400
You only have so many
editors and producers.

01:01:35.400 --> 01:01:39.670
Have you ever thought of maybe
tapping into your audience base

01:01:39.670 --> 01:01:43.080
and having maybe
grassroots reporters follow

01:01:43.080 --> 01:01:46.870
up on these stories to
give you more manpower to?

01:01:46.870 --> 01:01:48.430
IRA GLASS: No, we haven't.

01:01:48.430 --> 01:01:50.730
No, because generally,
I feel like it's rare

01:01:50.730 --> 01:01:52.980
for there to be a story like
that where there's people

01:01:52.980 --> 01:01:54.230
sitting in prison
at the end of it

01:01:54.230 --> 01:01:55.690
and you wonder, when are
they going to get out?

01:01:55.690 --> 01:01:56.648
What's going to happen?

01:01:56.648 --> 01:01:59.910
Generally, the stories end.

01:01:59.910 --> 01:02:02.160
In a very bratty way, I feel
like there's nothing else

01:02:02.160 --> 01:02:06.595
to say, and that's
the end of the story.

01:02:06.595 --> 01:02:07.470
You know what I mean?

01:02:07.470 --> 01:02:08.844
AUDIENCE: Do your
other producers

01:02:08.844 --> 01:02:10.250
and writers feel the same way?

01:02:10.250 --> 01:02:11.542
They feel like, OK, we're done.

01:02:11.542 --> 01:02:12.916
IRA GLASS: I
haven't polled them.

01:02:12.916 --> 01:02:14.017
I don't know.

01:02:14.017 --> 01:02:15.350
Maybe they do, maybe they don't.

01:02:15.350 --> 01:02:18.110
I mean, I can tell you that
when we do reruns, we do go back

01:02:18.110 --> 01:02:20.500
and we check with all the
characters in the stories.

01:02:20.500 --> 01:02:23.050
And we do that because
we made the mistake once

01:02:23.050 --> 01:02:25.720
of rerunning this story
about this couple,

01:02:25.720 --> 01:02:27.940
and then it turned out
one of them had died,

01:02:27.940 --> 01:02:30.730
and we were just like, oh no.

01:02:30.730 --> 01:02:33.167
That was years and years
ago, so now we go back

01:02:33.167 --> 01:02:34.250
and we check on everybody.

01:02:34.250 --> 01:02:37.790
So when we rerun that episode,
if we ever do, we'll go back

01:02:37.790 --> 01:02:39.640
and we'll know what
happened to them.

01:02:39.640 --> 01:02:43.785
But you yourself, if you're
so curious-- their names are

01:02:43.785 --> 01:02:44.410
in the stories.

01:02:44.410 --> 01:02:46.290
You can check it yourself.

01:02:46.290 --> 01:02:48.390
I don't know why I'm
putting this back on you.

01:02:53.692 --> 01:02:55.150
At "The New York
Times," they don't

01:02:55.150 --> 01:02:57.233
go back to everything in
the archive and tell you,

01:02:57.233 --> 01:02:59.440
here's what happened.

01:02:59.440 --> 01:03:01.020
I'm reacting very
defensively, which

01:03:01.020 --> 01:03:02.605
means you're probably right.

01:03:02.605 --> 01:03:05.790
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:05.790 --> 01:03:07.770
Yes?

01:03:07.770 --> 01:03:09.790
AUDIENCE: So what's
your one advice

01:03:09.790 --> 01:03:12.975
for improving
storytelling skills?

01:03:12.975 --> 01:03:14.850
IRA GLASS: Are you trying
to do storytelling?

01:03:14.850 --> 01:03:15.830
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:03:15.830 --> 01:03:17.470
IRA GLASS: In what
kind of context?

01:03:17.470 --> 01:03:19.360
AUDIENCE: Well, I
love storytelling,

01:03:19.360 --> 01:03:22.020
and I think you are the
best I've heard so far,

01:03:22.020 --> 01:03:24.470
so I wanted to get
one advice from you.

01:03:24.470 --> 01:03:25.930
IRA GLASS: See,
but in real life,

01:03:25.930 --> 01:03:27.430
I'm not a great storyteller.

01:03:27.430 --> 01:03:29.325
I'm only really
good on the radio.

01:03:31.860 --> 01:03:34.210
I need production
values for it to work.

01:03:34.210 --> 01:03:36.435
AUDIENCE: So your advice
is production value?

01:03:36.435 --> 01:03:38.235
IRA GLASS: Absolutely.

01:03:38.235 --> 01:03:40.100
If you can just get a
little music playing

01:03:40.100 --> 01:03:42.040
underneath as you talk.

01:03:42.040 --> 01:03:45.550
I mean, are you talking
about storytelling

01:03:45.550 --> 01:03:47.410
in your everyday life?

01:03:47.410 --> 01:03:49.080
AUDIENCE: No, more in writing.

01:03:49.080 --> 01:03:50.210
IRA GLASS: In writing.

01:03:50.210 --> 01:03:56.745
I mean, honestly, obviously,
the most important part

01:03:56.745 --> 01:03:57.995
is you want to amuse yourself.

01:04:02.530 --> 01:04:05.346
The storytelling we do,
I feel like if you're

01:04:05.346 --> 01:04:07.720
showing your stuff to friends
and they're honest with you

01:04:07.720 --> 01:04:09.680
about what's working
and what isn't,

01:04:09.680 --> 01:04:12.010
obviously, that's a huge help.

01:04:12.010 --> 01:04:13.830
I don't think I have
super smart tips

01:04:13.830 --> 01:04:15.830
that I can impart in a second.

01:04:15.830 --> 01:04:17.407
The things that
I'm interested in

01:04:17.407 --> 01:04:18.990
do have the kind of
structure that I'm

01:04:18.990 --> 01:04:21.210
saying, where it's
very plot based.

01:04:21.210 --> 01:04:24.680
I feel like that just gives
things an enormous power.

01:04:24.680 --> 01:04:26.340
That was a terrible answer.

01:04:26.340 --> 01:04:29.070
I'm so sorry.

01:04:29.070 --> 01:04:32.070
FEMALE SPEAKER:
And on that note--

01:04:32.070 --> 01:04:36.270
[LAUGHTER]

01:04:36.270 --> 01:04:39.429
[APPLAUSE]

01:04:39.429 --> 01:04:40.470
FEMALE SPEAKER: Good job.

01:04:40.470 --> 01:04:41.070
IRA GLASS: Thanks.

01:04:41.070 --> 01:04:41.370
FEMALE SPEAKER: That was fun.

01:04:41.370 --> 01:04:42.270
That was great.

01:04:42.270 --> 01:05:08.312
[MUSIC PLAYING]

